SubTopics: Determine a central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: Which statement is the BEST summary of the passage?

A.Choice: Searching for lost objects is similar to going on a treasure hunt without a map, a frustrating and time-consuming process. Moreover, researchers specializing in memory and cognition have studied this problem and identified some common habits among people who frequently misplace things.

B.Choice: Although it is normal for people to lose items at times, there are strategies people can use to help locate lost items. Experts recommend ways to search systematically and provide a few suggestions to prevent losing objects in the first place.

C.Choice: Items are lost every day, and the situation typically worsens as people age. To help find a lost item, experts recommend narrowing down the search area by avoiding places where the item is obviously not present and trying to remember where the object was last seen.

D.Choice: When seeking a lost object, people usually first look in less cluttered places. However, researchers suggest that people use other strategies to help find a lost item, such as searching in an area close to where the item is supposed to be and using colorful markings or technological aids.

SubTopics: Determine a central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: The following item has two parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
Which sentence BEST states a central idea in the passage?

A.Choice: People tend to panic when they need to find a lost item.

B.Choice: It is normal for people to misplace objects, but there are strategies to help find them.

C.Choice: Research has been done to determine why some people are forgetful, but there is no cure for forgetfulness yet.

D.Choice: Experts are beginning to understand why people lose things.

Content: Which quotation from the passage BEST helps develop this idea?

A.Choice: “'No matter how promising a site — if the object wasn't there the first time, it won't be there the second.'” (paragraph 13)

B.Choice: “Think about the location, what you were doing, the time of day, who else was there, your mental state and any other details.” (paragraph 18)

C.Choice: “If two people are searching, use open-ended instead of leading questions, she said.” (paragraph 21)

D.Choice: “'When you prepare for losing items — which we all do at all ages — you have a better chance of finding a marked-to-stand-out item, than one that camouflages itself into your décor.'” (paragraph 24)

SubTopics: Determine a central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: What is the central idea of the section titled “Focus on cluttered areas”?

A.Choice: People often waste time by searching for lost objects in unusual places.

B.Choice: People are more likely to lose small objects in a cluttered space than in an uncluttered one.

C.Choice: People can improve their searching skills by training their eyes to focus only on appropriate targets.

D.Choice: People tend to seek objects in relatively open and orderly spaces even when it is obvious the objects are not there.

SubTopics: Analyze how an author presents and develops key ideas and events to impact meaning.
Content: The following item has two parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
How does Devi's statement contradict the claim made by Irene Kan in paragraphs 17–19?

A.Choice: By introducing data from additional research studies

B.Choice: By asking questions that Kan has not considered

C.Choice: By explaining an unintended consequence of following Kan's advice

D.Choice: By offering proof of an alternate theory

Content: Which detail from the passage supports the answer to Part A?

B.Choice: “'The most efficient way to find something is not to look where you don't need to look ...'” (paragraph 16)

C.Choice: “... the key to finding misplaced items is forming a mental image of what you were doing or feeling when you last saw the missing item.” (paragraph 17)

D.Choice: “... recreating those moments can sometimes introduce a false memory that takes you off the trail.” (paragraph 20)
